e range of approaches to medieval warfare. They include traditional studies of strategy (on Baybars) and the logistics of Edward II's wars, as well as cultural history (an examination of chivalry in Guy of Warwick) intellectual history (a broad analysis of strategic theory in the Middle Ages), and social history (on knightly training in arms). The Hundred Years War is studied using cutting-edge methodology (data-drivenanalysis of skirmishes) and by tackling relatively new areas of inquiry (environmental history). There is also a close reading of Carolingian documents, which sheds new light on armies and warfare in the time of Charles the Great. Contributors: Ronald W. Braasch III, Pierre Galle, Walter Goffart, Carl I. Hammer, John Hosler, Rabei G. Khamisy, Ilana Krug, Danny Lake-Giguère, Brian Price.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aMilitary history, Medieval. 4aMedieval History. 4aMilitary History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCarolingian Documents.  aChivalry.  aEnvironmental History.  aHundred Years War.  aIntellectual History.  aJournal.  aLogistics.  aMedieval Warfare.  aMilitary History.  aStrategy.1 aBraasch, Ronald W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeVries, Kelly, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFrance, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGaite, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoffart, Walter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammer, Carl I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammer, Carl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHosler, John D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhamisy, Rabei G., econtributor.